etymologies: Old English (in an earlier sense). Originally (i) cognate with or formed similarly to Old High German unmāzi huge, immeasurable (Middle High German unmāze, unmaēze) from the Germanic base of un- + the Germanic base of Old English maēte mean, moderate, poor, inferior, small, bad;

definitions: Not having or showing the necessary qualities or skills for something; incompetent; unworthy. Now archaic and somewhat rare. With † to (preposition) or to with infinitive.
With to (preposition) or to with infinitive (often with anticipatory it).
